{"key":"post-12772380","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12772380</id>\n<content>You can use food grade gypsum for brewing, but it's much more expensive than the agricultural gypsum that is fine for our use.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you're doing old-style grain jars where you simply put dry grains and water in a jar and sterilize, use a pinch of gypsum between your thumb and forefinger in each jar.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you're doing a more modern technique such as the one shown in the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Grain-Preparation&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;grain prep video&lt;/a&gt;, use about a tablespoon or so in the soak water.&amp;nbsp; A bit more won't hurt, it just won't do any good either.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>12772096</prev>\n<first>12772047</first>\n<last>12772380</last>\n<when>1277038295</when>\n<utime>06/20/10 03:51 PM</utime>\n</post>"}